<br>
And to the person that said that these foriegn companies didn't give because they wouldn't receive a tax break?  Jesus. <br>
<br>
What was the worst attack on US soil in United States History. More lives were lost, more terror was caused, and more of a dollar value than any attack ever. <br>
<br>
We let these companies do business in the United States - and these people here buy these cars from foreign companies. The majority of their business is conducted in the United States - and when something like this happens, they should have given something to help out the disaster recovery.  <br>
<br>
However in my dealings with American made cars compared with Japanese and foriegn, I have had much better luck with foriegn based cars. For example my girlfriend's 96 Grand Prix just went in to have a Head gasket replaced, a new radiator, <br>
and a new clutch with just over 70,000 miles on it.  My winter car, a 1992 Honda Accord EX, with over 150,000 miles has yet to have any problem what so ever.  Both were taken care of to the letter. <br>
<br>
I have seen american made cars bite the big one every 3-4 years - while I still see the quality of foriegn made vehicles. <br>
<br>
I agree that these companies which we buy things from definately should have put something into the pot. However, it will not make me support a company that makes a shit product.  If these american car makers would get their head out of their ass and make a quality, long lasting affordable vehicle, than I am sure more people would be buying these cars. <br>
<br>
Course this could be all based on the luck of the draw. But my family, friends and acquaintances have yet to get a lemon- while the same that buy American made cars are always complaining about break down within 3-4 years.  Iam a consumer just like everyone else, and I am not going to spend 30k on a carthat in 3 years will have problems - when I can spend 30k for a foriegn car that will last 200% longer. <br>
